The algorithm starts by checking if the input number n is less than or equal to 0. If it is, then it is not a power of three, so we return false. 

Next, we enter a while loop that continues until n is no longer divisible by 3 (i.e., n % 3 == 0). In each iteration of the loop, we divide n by 3. This has the effect of reducing n to its lowest power of three equivalent. For example, if n = 27, then the loop will divide n by 3 three times, resulting in n = 1, which is the lowest power of three equivalent of 27.

Once the loop breaks, we check if n is equal to 1. If it is, then this means that n was originally a power of three, and we return true. Otherwise, n must be a multiple of 3 but not a power of three, so we return false.

